==English==

===Etymology===
First attested around 1439. From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|abjuracioun|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{term/t|la|abiūrātiō||forswearing, abjuration}}, from {{term|ab||from, away from|lang=la}} + {{term/t|la|iūrō||swear or take an oath}}, from {{term/t|la|iūs||law, right, duty}}. Compare French ''[[abjuration#French|abjuration]]''.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ˌæb.d͡ʒʊˈreɪ.ʃn̩/|/ˌæb.d͡ʒəˈreɪ.ʃn̩/|/ˌæb.d͡ʒʊɹˈɹeɪ.ʃn̩/}}
* {{rhymes|eɪʃən}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A solemn [[recantation]] or [[renunciation]] on oath; as, an '''abjuration''' of [[heresy]]. {{defdate|First attested around 1350 to 1470.}}<ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=5}}</ref>
# A repudiation on oath of a religious or political principle. {{defdate|Mid 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
# The act of [[abjure|abjuring]].

